<div id="review_1869516579" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1869516579" />
    <a title="CM" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8482935-cm"><img alt="CM" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1588343180p2/8482935.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1869516579?book_show_action=true">Feb 05, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="CM" class="user" itemprop="url" name="CM" href="/user/show/8482935-cm">CM</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/18658663-under-the-jaguar-sun">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8482935-cm?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1869516579" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8117322538652807630">3 stories here. Each story is closely related to one of the five senses. Calvino&apos;s description of all these senses is refined but not as charming as how he interweaves these senses into the narratives.<br/><br/>a)Under the Jaguar Sun----***** <br/>This is a story of taste and meals. A man travels with his female partner, Olivia, in Mexico and this man connects their trip,especially their meals and the myth of human sacrifice of the Aztec(an obsession of Olivia), to the power dynamics of their relationship. <br/><br/> <i>&quot;W</i></span>
  <span id="freeText8117322538652807630" style="display:none">3 stories here. Each story is closely related to one of the five senses. Calvino's description of all these senses is refined but not as charming as how he interweaves these senses into the narratives.<br /><br />a)Under the Jaguar Sun----***** <br />This is a story of taste and meals. A man travels with his female partner, Olivia, in Mexico and this man connects their trip,especially their meals and the myth of human sacrifice of the Aztec(an obsession of Olivia), to the power dynamics of their relationship. <br /><br /> <i>"What I have just said[about Olivia's dining posture] might suggest that, in eating, Olivia became closed into herself, absorbed with the inner course of her sensations; in reality, on the contrary, the desire her whole person expressed was that of communicating to me what she was tasting: communicating with me through flavors, or communicating with flavors through a double set of taste buds, hers and mine."</i><br /><br />b)A King Listens----****<br />A second-person narrative(not exactly a story here) about a king sitting and then listening to the surroundings on his throne. It begins with humour, with the narrator cautioning you not to drop the scepter :<i>"hardly a pretty sight to see a king stretched out on the floor to reach it"</i> or the crown :<i>When you feel it is about to slip, you have to be clever enough to adjust its position with little twitches of the head"</i>. It soon becomes much darker when isolation and paranoia set in. <br /><br /><i>"The palace is a construction of sounds that expands one moment and contracts the next, tightened like a tangle of chains. You can move though it, guided by the echoes, localizing creaks, clangs, curses, pursuing breaths, rustles, grumbles, gurgles. The palace is the body of the king. Your body sends you mysterious messages, which you receive with fear, with anxiety. In an unknown part of this body, a menace is lurking, your death is already stationed there; the signals that reach you warn you perhaps of a danger buried in your own posterior." </i><br /><br />Then a tune comes and the king will finally leave his throne.<br />(This one is more nightmarish and you may say it appears to be a bad dream of someone, maybe of a dethroned king?)<br /><br />c)The Name, The Nose ----(****)<br />Three men, a modern musician, a caveman and a socialite, are on their pursuit of a female based on her scent,leading to an unexpected end.<br /><br /><i>"For each woman a perfume exists which enhances the perfume of her own skin, the note in the scale which is at once color and aroma and flavor and tenderness, and thus the pleasure in moving from one skin to another can be endless."</i><br /><br /><br />A polished,first-rate collection it is. It's a pity that he couldn't finish all five senses owed to his health.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8117322538652807630" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


