    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_59707849" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/59707849" />
    <a title="Rhys" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1138007-rhys"><img alt="Rhys" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442456315p2/1138007.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/59707849?book_show_action=true">Jun 15, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rhys" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rhys" href="/user/show/1138007-rhys">Rhys</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer59707849" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4774038198508637869">Not the finest Calvino book by any means. That&apos;s because it&apos;s a slight piece of art in the sense that it&apos;s an unfinished project... But in her Afterword, Esther Calvino asks for readers to regard this book not in that manner but rather as three standalone (though connected) short stories. That&apos;s exactly how they would be read if they were included with other stories in a larger collection (maybe they should have been part of the *Numbers in the Dark* collection?)<br/><br/>The truth is that the very act of</span>
  <span id="freeText4774038198508637869" style="display:none">Not the finest Calvino book by any means. That's because it's a slight piece of art in the sense that it's an unfinished project... But in her Afterword, Esther Calvino asks for readers to regard this book not in that manner but rather as three standalone (though connected) short stories. That's exactly how they would be read if they were included with other stories in a larger collection (maybe they should have been part of the *Numbers in the Dark* collection?)<br /><br />The truth is that the very act of revealing that these three stories were intended to form part of a fully integrated story-cycle dealing with the five senses means that the reader can't help but try to imagine what the two missing stories (concerning sight and touch) might have been like, and how all the stories would have fitted together within one of Calvino's justly celebrated framing devices... It would have been a remarkable collection, of that I'm sure, and probably even superior to *Mr Palomar*.<br /><br />So we are left with the three short stories as they are. They are good, very good, but not among Calvino's best. 'Under the Jaguar Sun' is a superior version of the somewhat overdone food-as-dangerous-eroticism theme and is mostly enjoyable for the fact that it is wholly conventional in terms of structure, dialogue, character interaction, and therefore quite un-Calvinoesque, demonstrating his sheer range and versatility. Both Modern and Ancient Mexico are evoked extremely effectively in a short space.<br /><br />The second tale, 'A King Listens', is much more typical of vintage cerebral Calvino. Probably the best story in the book (but not my favourite) its main conceit is how power can be limiting rather than liberating. The central concept of a king unable to leave his throne room, not even permitted to vacate his throne, and forced to interpret the rest of palace life and the outside world through the random sounds that reach him along passages that resemble the conduits of the human ear, is superb and deeply strange.<br /><br />The third story is my favourite, though it is also less typically Calvinoesque. 'The Name, The Nose' is concerned with a man in several incarnations throughout time (or perhaps several different men or beings) who are on the trail of an elusive and special feminine perfume. In some ways it anticpates Patrick Suskind but it's far more concise in every way. The juxtaposition of prehistoric savannah life, elegant turn of the century Paris and bohemian London in the 60s is original and brilliant.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4774038198508637869" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


