  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_625548487" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/625548487" />
    <a title="Emma" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7949813-emma"><img alt="Emma" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1509994667p2/7949813.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/625548487?book_show_action=true">May 26, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Emma" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Emma" href="/user/show/7949813-emma">Emma</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer625548487" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15883168547086917990">I don&apos;t know if I would refer to my reading experience of this collection of short stories as enjoyable, but it was interesting and unsettling. &apos;Under the Jaguar Sun&apos; is a collection of three stories, each of which focuses on a different &apos;sense&apos;. This is an unfinished project as Calvino sadly passed away before its completion. <br/><br/>I found the first tale, the one from which the collection&apos;s name is derived, was my favourite. This opening story deals with taste and it&apos;s ability to drive hunger for foo</span>
  <span id="freeText15883168547086917990" style="display:none">I don't know if I would refer to my reading experience of this collection of short stories as enjoyable, but it was interesting and unsettling. 'Under the Jaguar Sun' is a collection of three stories, each of which focuses on a different 'sense'. This is an unfinished project as Calvino sadly passed away before its completion. <br /><br />I found the first tale, the one from which the collection's name is derived, was my favourite. This opening story deals with taste and it's ability to drive hunger for food, passion and knowledge, it takes a peculiar and macabre turn as the protagonists get caught up in an imagined frenzy of cannibalism. Very odd, yet somehow satisfying. I struggled to obtain a clear understanding of the second tale, 'A King Listens', not ever really working out whether this was a tale of madness and inner voices or otherwise. As for the third tale, 'The Name, The Nose', this was perhaps the darkest, most sinister one of the trio as an exploration of scent takes its protagonists through discovery, passion and loss, all judged by the scent of their desire. I was shocked by the conclusion of this tale of ill fate and smell, it will most likely come back to me when people talk of things that terrify and repulse. Very, very surreal, yet somehow exciting.<br /><br />The prose itself had a lyrical, pleasing flow in the majority, yet there were times where the style became disjointed and my mind wandered. There is an underlying sexual theme in two of the tales, possibly even all three but as I struggled in my understanding I wouldn't like to say for sure, and Calvino explores primal instincts to draw shocking comparisons with contemporary life. This primal theme is particularly clear in the 'smell' tale and is reasonably obvious in the other two. The intensity of the the tales increases, the first is slow yet calculated, the second story is vexatious and jittery, and by the time you reach the third tale the prose hurtles like a rocket through it's eccentric events and I was barely able to keep up. <br /><br />This is by no means a polished piece of work, but it is a curious one and it has its macabre charm. Well worth exploring and at only 80 pages it is an afternoon read that won't take up too much of your time should you want to give it a go. Perfect if you want a snap shot of some literary weirdness.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15883168547086917990" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

