<div id="review_370431393" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/370431393" />
    <a title="Bryan Serwatka" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9583928-bryan-serwatka"><img alt="Bryan Serwatka" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442627757p2/9583928.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/370431393?book_show_action=true">Jul 17, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bryan Serwatka" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bryan Serwatka" href="/user/show/9583928-bryan-serwatka">Bryan Serwatka</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer370431393" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4451292026993070175">This is a compilation (or so it seemed) of three short stories Calvino wrote in his final years. I hadn&apos;t ever read anything of Calvino&apos;s and only really picked the book off the shelf because of the title and shocking description. I found his (translated) style rather flowery and almost painfully educated to the point of being simultaneously impressed by the vocabulary and depressed by my own.<br/><br/>I found the first story, Under the Jaguar Sun, completely enthralling, but I couldn&apos;t decide if I was so</span>
  <span id="freeText4451292026993070175" style="display:none">This is a compilation (or so it seemed) of three short stories Calvino wrote in his final years. I hadn't ever read anything of Calvino's and only really picked the book off the shelf because of the title and shocking description. I found his (translated) style rather flowery and almost painfully educated to the point of being simultaneously impressed by the vocabulary and depressed by my own.<br /><br />I found the first story, Under the Jaguar Sun, completely enthralling, but I couldn't decide if I was so personally involved in the story due to my love of the keen focus on the flavours of Mexican cuisine. Being a Texan abroad, I haughtily take it upon myself to be an authority on anything Texan, American or Mexican that I encounter on this side of the Atlantic. Such a stance has never caused me any joy, only condescending disappointment particularly when it comes to food. I really need to get over myself. Anyway, I found the sparse dialogue and pervasive obsession over Aztec ritual human sacrifices fascinating. <br /><br />Disappointingly, I found the second story, A King Listens, a tedious read. I love obsession in literature - I really do - but the king's obsession in the story seemed to flirt too much with a twee, sentimental infatuation that to me didn't seem convincing. But maybe that's just me. Structurally, mathematically, Calvino designed this story and the preoccupations of the king on the sounds of the castle as perfectly as humanly possible. Still, I just couldn't enjoy it. Never has a short story felt so long.<br /><br />'The Name, The Nose,' the final story, had gripped me from the start. What a brilliant, creative story! It was only here that I realised these stories all dealt with physical senses. This one spans from prehistory to the modern day following three men captured by the scent of a woman. I really loved this and don't want to write too much about it. Just read it.<br /><br />An afterword written by Calvino's wife after his death told of Italo's plan to create a novel of different stories (including these three) based on the five senses.* From notes written days before falling ill, his story remained unfinished due to structure, or a 'frame' as he put it.<br /><br />*Reading this, I couldn't help but think of Kieslowski's unfinished films.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4451292026993070175" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

